\pard\nowidctlpar Say we have two positive numbers A and B. And let's assume A>B.  Then we can write A as a multiple of B plus a remainder R. For example, if A=98, B= 10, then 98 can be written 90 + 8 where 90 is a multiple of 10 and the remainder R is 8.  Note that R is always strictly less than B otherwise we can still pull a B out of R.  By that we mean usually we won't write 98 as 80 + 18 because you can still get a 10 out of 18.  A long way to look at this is: say I have $98 and want to buy as many large cheese pizza as possible. If each large cheese pizza costs $10, how many pizzas can I buy and how much money will be left.  Can you convince yourself that I can buy at most 9 pizzas with $8 left?\par
\par
The above is the concept of remainder.  So for any positive integers A>B, we can write A=m*B + R where m is another positive integer and R is the remainder  (0<=R<B). In the pizza example, m=9 is the number of pizzas that I can buy while R=8 is the money left.  Now here's an important observation: every common factor of A and B is also a factor of R; and every common factor B and R is also a factor of A. Can you convince yourself to accept this?\par
\par
With this observation, we can say that GCD of A and B is exactly the GCD of B and R.  It would be nice to deal with B and R because they are smaller than A and B. Think about 10 and 8 v.s. 98 and 10.  If B and R are still too big, we can apply this remainder process again until they become sufficiently small. This process is the Euclidean algorithm.\par

\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-360\li720\par

