\pard\nowidctlpar Unfortunately factoring "large" numbers is very difficult. Of course, the definition of "large" depends on your skill, experience and most importantly what kind of tool do you have. \par
If you just do mental calculation, then factoring a number close to 1000 would be quite difficult for most people; if you have paper and pencil, then you can handle much larger ones;\par
if you have a good computer and can write computer programs, then factoring a number at the order of million would be a piece of cake. \par
One catch in factoring a relative large number is to notice that it must have a factor that's less than or equal to its square root. For example, say I want to factor 1147. First I find or \par
roughly guess its square root which is around 33. Then I'll test from 33 to 1 to find the first factor of 1147. After some calculation, we can see that 31 is a factor of 1147 which leads to 1147=31*37.\par
\par
As I mentioned in my previous post, factoring a "large" number is very difficult. Interestingly, this difficulty finds application in cryptography. For example,say, the key to decrypt a message depends on whether you can factor the number 489527 since one factor will lead to the key.  Without a computer, it's going to take a while for ordinary people to factor it. Therefore this is pretty secure against \par
computer-less attack. For real applications, the number has to be really really big so that even with a computer it's very hard to factor. Of course, we can always find numbers that are sufficiently large since positive integers can go to infinity.  \par
See {{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_Factoring_Challenge }}{\fldrslt{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_Factoring_Challenge\ul0\cf0}}}}\f0\fs24  for interesting challenge related to this topic.\par

