\pard\nowidctlpar There is one way that can be used to find the GCF of two integers with probably less factoring.  This method uses the concept of remainder which I believe that you have learned.\par
If not, see {{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK http://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/division-remainder.html }}{\fldrslt{http://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/division-remainder.html\ul0\cf0}}}}\f0\fs24  for an explanation. Here are a few simple examples: the remainder of 7 divided by 2 is 1, the remainder of 13 divided by 5 is 3, the remainder of 16 divided by 4 is 0.\par
\par
Now let's say I want to find GCF(m,n) where m and n are two integers and m>n.  Let r be the remainder of m divided by n. Then if r=0, we know n is a factor of m so n itself is the CCF (why?); if r>0, then there is a theorem stating GCF(m,n) = GCF(n,r) which will replace the bigger number m by the smaller number r. \par
\par
Using your example: GCF(36,24)=?\par
The remainder of 36 divided by 24 is 12, so GCF(36,24)=GCF(24,12). Now since 12 is a factor of 24, so GCF(24,12)=12, i.e. GCF(36,24)=12.\par
\par
Now the numbers n and r are still too big, we can apply this reduction process repetitively until they become sufficiently small.\par
\par

\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-360\li720 Prime factorization is very important in mathematics especially for number theory. The theorem states that every integer>1 can be factorized into a sequence of prime number(s). If that sequence only contains the original number, then that number is a prime number itself. This seems to be an obvious fact.  Interestingly, we can use it to prove that there are infinitely many prime numbers:\par

\pard\nowidctlpar            Now suppose there are only n prime numbers p1,p2, .... pn. We can create another number P=p1*p2*p3.....*pn + 1.  Clearly P is bigger than any one of the known prime number and none of the prime is a factor of P. Therefore P has to be a prime itself which contradicts with the assumption that p1-pn are all primes. Hence there are infinitely many primes.\par

