\pard\nowidctlpar Generally to factor a trinomial   a x^2 + b x + c where a is not 1, you have to try all possible ways to factor a and c. \par
The following is the reason.  If a x^2 + bx + c can indeed be factored, then we can write it as \par
a x^2 + b x + c = (m x + g) (n x + t) for some m, g, n, t. And our job is to find these four numbers or show that they don't exist.\par
Expanding the right hand side gives  (mn) x + (mt + gn)x + gt.  Comparing this with a x^2 + b x + c, we see that we need to find numbers such that \par
(1) a = mn\par
(2) c = gt\par
(3) b = mt + gn.\par
\par
(1)  and (2) are easy because they only involve factoring an integer a (or c).  So this is the basic routine. \par
(i) find all possible ways to factor a, in other words, all candidates of (m, n)\par
(ii) find all possible ways to factor c, in other words, all candidates of (g, t) \par
(iii)  check whether there is a pair (m,n ) and a pair (g, t) such that b = mt + gn. If so, then we find our factoring.  If not,  then the original\par
trinomial cannot be factored.\par
\par
3x^2 + 7x + 2 is relatively simple because here a = 3 and c = 2 are prime numbers. \par
So here goes:\par
(i) a = 3, the candidates of (m, n) are (3, 1) (1, 3), (-3, - 1), (-1, -3).\par
(ii) c = 2, the candidates of (g, t) are (2, 1) (1, 2), (-2, -1), (-1, -2).\par
(iii) After some calculation, we see that  (m=3, n=1) and (g=1, t = 2) satisfies mt+gn = 3*2 + 1*1 = 7 =b. So our facoring is \par
3x^2 + 7x + 2 = (3x + 1) (x+2).\par
\par
It appears that lots of calculations are needed.  After sufficient practice, for relatively small numbers, you usually can quickly\par
go through most possibliites in mind.  There are different ways to lay out this strategy, but essentially it is the only method. \par
When the numbers are very large and have many factors, the problem becomes very difficult. But that won't happen in this course.\par
